15-year-olds to be added to Scottish independence electoral roll
A separate and confidential electoral register that includes children aged as young as 15 will be drawn up for the Scottish independence referendum, under legislation published today. 16 and 17-year-olds will vote in the independence referendum Photo: PA	By Simon Johnson, Scottish Political Editor
12:09PM GMT 12 Mar 2013
Comments
All households north of the Border will receive a form asking parents to identify teenagers who will reach 16 by the time of the referendum, which is due to be staged in autumn next year. Their details will be held on a separate Register of Young Voters (RYV), which will be used to give 16 and 17-year-olds a ballot in the referendum.
Amid concern about gathering the personal details of minors, including their dates of birth and addresses, the information will not be made public so it cannot be used by the likes of marketing companies.
The two main referendum campaigns will be given access but the RYV names will be mixed in with the main electoral register so they cannot tell who is a minor.
The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Bill gives British and EU citizens resident in Scotland the right to vote along with armed forces personnel serving elsewhere who are registered for a ballot north of the Border. Related Articles
