Michael Owen: why I love the madness and exhilaration of transfer deadline day
It can be mad, exhilarating - and not always glamorous - but last-minute scramble is an essential part of football
New start: Michael Owen is unveiled by Newcastle after transfer window signing Photo: PA	By Michael Owen
8:41PM GMT 31 Jan 2014
Follow Comments
There are those who see transfer deadline day as a bit of circus. Full of hype, manufactured drama and creating an unseemly spectacle as players are herded around like cattle.
Critics should get off their pedestal, take a step back and enjoy it for what it is – one of the most entertaining and theatrical dates in our football calendar. The manner in which supporters have become so engaged in the transfer process is healthy for the sport.
Only our passion for football can prompt us to spend a Friday night sitting on the sofa diligently watching a yellow ticker go across our television set, or constantly update our Twitter feed to see whether that much coveted striker has finally signed on loan (usually with a view to a permanent deal).
Yes it is a bit irrational and you can ask yourself why you have spent hours staring at your screen when, in essence, not a lot has happened, but we’re all football fans and we all love digesting every bit of gossip that comes our way.
I have sat in the pubs with friends watching the deadline day coverage as if we were enjoying the match itself and it will be same across the country as we debate the best deals, arguing as to whether each club has bought the right player.
