Deadline day condenses months of speculation into a few hours and the media coverage is increasingly like a General Election, reporters dispatched across the country awaiting news of a possible medical in the way we used to wait for the first exit polls from the constituencies.
Personally, I love it and I am as absorbed as anyone by the hype. If it is ‘manufactured’ for a TV audience it is entirely by accident and due to the clubs themselves who, for their own reasons, decide to wait until the last minute of the last day to pursue their targets. If the clubs conducted their business in a less frenzied way we could all congratulate them on their organisation but it would not be so much fun.
The nature of sport being as it is, it wouldn’t matter if the transfer window was open for one month or six, you will end up with a panicky wave of activity in the last few hours.
Tough negotiators will always take it to the brink, playing on the desperation of the buying or selling club. You can imagine the battle of egos between chief executives trying to get that extra few million from their rival.
Caught in the middle are the players, most of whom involved in Friday’s transfers will have spent the day in a car, in some cases trying to avoid being spotted by a camera.
I speak from experience. I enjoyed the full glamour of deadline day when I signed for Stoke in September 2012.
It was approaching 4pm, the window about to close, and I was sitting in my car at a service station on the M6, waiting for the call to head to the training ground to complete the formalities of a free transfer.
Technically, I could have joined a club at any time because I was not under contract but the squad submissions needed to be sent to the Premier League so I was caught up in the mania.
I could not drive into the city for fear of being spotted, knowing if the deal did not go ahead people would be looking at me in the same way as Peter Odemwingie with his aborted move to Queens Park Rangers.
Fortunately, the call was made and the deal went through, but this is how Friday would have been for many footballers, hanging around, trying to maintain a veil of secrecy until such time the contracts can be signed.
I had a similar but not quite so time-sensitive experience seven years earlier when I moved to Newcastle from Real Madrid. This time the now infamous helicopter came into play as I headed to St James’ Park 24 hours before the transfer window closed.
As someone who did not make too many transfers during his career, I can’t say I particularly embraced the uncertainty of moving from one club to another. For a player, there can be no more anxious time as you have an eye on the clock and you are staring at your phone waiting for that significant call. For other players who are desperate to get away for a fresh challenge, the countdown to January may begin early in the season.
I don’t agree with the complaints about the timing of the transfer windows and believe it is essential for the integrity of the league to keep one in midseason.
The wealthiest clubs will always be in a position to target the best players, but ensuring they have a limited time to do so is fair to everyone.
You can’t go back to a situation where clubs have until March to secure deals, especially now we’re in an era where bids of £50 million have become common. The more vulnerable clubs would simply live in fear of having their most prized assets being lured away for virtually the whole season, often when they are at their most vulnerable. The old system could be too easily exploited.
Equally, it is interesting how most of the transfer activity in January is at the lower end of the division, those in the most trouble taking the opportunity to correct the flaws in their squad and give themselves a realistic chance of survival.
Everyone is abiding by the same rules, aware of when they can buy and how long they have to make it happen. It is as fair as it can be.
That so many deals make it to the 11th hour is a peculiarity of football. No doubt the most qualified business minds shake their head in incredulity at the madness of it all. Maybe the transfer system does defy logic, but it makes for brilliant television twice a season.
